The paper deals with the computational power of population protocols, which are a type of distributed computing model. This falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). However, the paper specifically focuses on the analysis of the predicates that can be stably computed in these protocols, which involves concepts from discrete mathematics and graph theory. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper discusses variants of the model in which agents communicate by anonymous message-passing, which involves concepts from information theory and communication theory, suggesting that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of Information Theory (cs.IT) and Signal Processing (cs.SP). Finally, the paper uses techniques from formal language theory and automata theory to prove its main result, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Computational Complexity (cs.CC).
